# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wavelet-tree-succinct
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] A **bitmap index** is a special kind of database index that uses bitmaps.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes have traditionally been considered to work well for *low-cardinality columns*, which have a modest number of distinct values, either absolutely, or relative to the number of records that contain the data.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The extreme case of low cardinality is Boolean data (e.g., does a resident in a city have internet access?), which has two values, True and False.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes use bit arrays (commonly called bitmaps) and answer queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes have a significant space and performance advantage over other structures for query of such data.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Some researchers argue that bitmap indexes are also useful for moderate or even high-cardinality data (e.g., unique-valued data) which is accessed in a read-only manner, and queries access multiple bitmap-indexed columns using the AND, OR or XOR operators extensively.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Bitmap indexes are also useful in data warehousing applications for joining a large fact table to smaller dimension tables such as those arranged in a star schema.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] On the left, Identifier refers to the unique number assigned to each resident, HasInternet is the data to be indexed, the content of the bitmap index is shown as two columns under the heading *bitmaps*.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Each column in the left illustration under the Bitmaps header is a *bitmap* in the bitmap index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In this case, there are two such bitmaps, one for "has internet" *Yes* and one for "has internet" *No*.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] It is easy to see that each bit in bitmap *Y* shows whether a particular row refers to a person who has internet access.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] This is the simplest form of bitmap index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Most columns will have more distinct values.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For example, the sales amount is likely to have a much larger number of distinct values.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Variations on the bitmap index can effectively index this data as well.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] We briefly review three such variations.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Note: Many of the references cited here are reviewed at (John Wu (2007)).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For those who might be interested in experimenting with some of the ideas mentioned here, many of them are implemented in open source software such as FastBit, the Lemur Bitmap Index C++ Library, the Roaring Bitmap Java library and the Apache Hive Data Warehouse system.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For historical reasons, bitmap compression and inverted list compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Software can compress each bitmap in a bitmap index to save space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] There has been considerable amount of work on this subject.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] These compression methods require very little effort to compress and decompress.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] More importantly, bitmaps compressed with BBC, WAH, COMPAX, PLWAH, EWAH and CONCISE can directly participate in bitwise operations without decompression.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] This gives them considerable advantages over generic compression techniques such as LZ77.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] BBC compression and its derivatives are used in a commercial database management system.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] BBC is effective in both reducing index sizes and maintaining query performance.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] BBC encodes the bitmaps in bytes, while WAH encodes in words, better matching current CPUs.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Similar considerations can be done for CONCISE and Enhanced Word-Aligned Hybrid.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The performance of schemes such as BBC, WAH, PLWAH, EWAH, COMPAX and CONCISE is dependent on the order of the rows.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] A simple lexicographical sort can divide the index size by 9 and make indexes several times faster.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The larger the table, the more important it is to sort the rows.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Reshuffling techniques have also been proposed to achieve the same results of sorting when indexing streaming data.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Basic bitmap indexes use one bitmap for each distinct value.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] It is possible to reduce the number of bitmaps used by using a different encoding method.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For example, it is possible to encode C distinct values using log(C) bitmaps with binary encoding.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] This reduces the number of bitmaps, further saving space, but to answer any query, most of the bitmaps have to be accessed.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] This makes it potentially not as effective as scanning a vertical projection of the base data, also known as a materialized view or projection index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Finding the optimal encoding method that balances (arbitrary) query performance, index size and index maintenance remains a challenge.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For high-cardinality columns, it is useful to bin the values, where each bin covers multiple values and build the bitmaps to represent the values in each bin.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] This approach reduces the number of bitmaps used regardless of encoding method.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] However, binned indexes can only answer some queries without examining the base data.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For example, if a bin covers the range from 0.1 to 0.2, then when the user asks for all values less than 0.15, all rows that fall in the bin are possible hits and have to be checked to verify whether they are actually less than 0.15.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The process of checking the base data is known as the candidate check.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In most cases, the time used by the candidate check is significantly longer than the time needed to work with the bitmap index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Therefore, binned indexes exhibit irregular performance.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] They can be very fast for some queries, but much slower if the query does not exactly match a bin.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The concept of bitmap index was first introduced by Professor Israel Spiegler and Rafi Maayan in their research "Storage and Retrieval Considerations of Binary Data Bases", published in 1985.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The first commercial database product to implement a bitmap index was Computer Corporation of America's Model 204.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Patrick O'Neil published a paper about this implementation in 1987.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] This implementation is a hybrid between the basic bitmap index (without compression) and the list of Row Identifiers (RID-list).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Overall, the index is organized as a B+tree.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] When the column cardinality is low, each leaf node of the B-tree would contain long list of RIDs.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In this case, it requires less space to represent the RID-lists as bitmaps.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Since each bitmap represents one distinct value, this is the basic bitmap index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] As the column cardinality increases, each bitmap becomes sparse and it may take more disk space to store the bitmaps than to store the same content as RID-lists.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In this case, it switches to use the RID-lists, which makes it a B+tree index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] One of the strongest reasons for using bitmap indexes is that the intermediate results produced from them are also bitmaps and can be efficiently reused in further operations to answer more complex queries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Many programming languages support this as a bit array data structure.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For example, Java has the `BitSet` class and .NET have the BitArray class.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Some database systems that do not offer persistent bitmap indexes use bitmaps internally to speed up query processing.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] For example, PostgreSQL versions 8.1 and later implement a "bitmap index scan" optimization to speed up arbitrarily complex logical operations between available indexes on a single table.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] A bitmap index scan combines expressions on different indexes, thus requiring only one index per column to support all possible queries on a table.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Applying this access strategy to B-tree indexes can also combine range queries on multiple columns.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In this approach, a temporary in-memory bitmap is created with one bit for each row in the table (1 MB can thus store over 8 million entries).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Next, the results from each index are combined into the bitmap using bitwise operations.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] After all conditions are evaluated, the bitmap contains a "1" for rows that matched the expression.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] Finally, the bitmap is traversed and matching rows are retrieved.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In addition to efficiently combining indexes, this also improves locality of reference of table accesses, because all rows are fetched sequentially from the main table.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] The internal bitmap is discarded after the query.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] If there are too many rows in the table to use 1 bit per row, a "lossy" bitmap is created instead, with a single bit per disk page.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap-index] In this case, the bitmap is just used to determine which pages to fetch; the filter criteria are then applied to all rows in matching pages.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] In computing, a **bitmap** (also called **raster**) graphic is an image formed from rows of different colored pixels.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] A GIF is an example of a graphics image file that uses a bitmap.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] As a noun, the term "bitmap" is very often used to refer to a particular bitmapping application: the **pix-map**, which refers to a map of pixels, where each pixel may store more than two colors, thus using more than one bit per pixel.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] In such a case, the domain in question is the array of pixels which constitute a digital graphic output device (a screen or monitor).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] In some contexts, the term *bitmap* implies one bit per pixel, whereas *pixmap* is used for images with multiple bits per pixel.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] A bitmap is a type of memory organization or image file format used to store digital images.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] The term *bitmap* comes from the computer programming terminology, meaning just a *map of bits*, a spatially mapped array of bits.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Now, along with *pixmap*, it commonly refers to the similar concept of a spatially mapped array of pixels.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Raster images in general may be referred to as bitmaps or pixmaps, whether synthetic or photographic, in files or memory.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Many graphical user interfaces use bitmaps in their built-in graphics subsystems.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] For example, the Microsoft Windows and OS/2 platforms' GDI subsystem uses the *Windows and OS/2 bitmap file format*, usually named with the file extension `.BMP` (or `.DIB` for *device-independent bitmap*).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Besides BMP, other file formats that store literal bitmaps include InterLeaved Bitmap (ILBM), Portable Bitmap (PBM), X Bitmap (XBM), and Wireless Application Protocol Bitmap (WBMP).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Similarly, most other image file formats, such as JPEG, TIFF, PNG, and GIF, also store bitmap images (as opposed to vector graphics), but they are not usually referred to as *bitmaps*, since they use compressed formats internally.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] In typical uncompressed bitmaps, image pixels are generally stored with a variable number of bits per pixel which identify its color (the color depth).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Pixels of 8 bits and fewer can represent either grayscale or indexed color.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] An alpha channel (for transparency) may be stored in a separate bitmap, where it is similar to a grayscale bitmap, or in a fourth channel that, for example, converts 24-bit images to 32 bits per pixel.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] The bits representing the bitmap pixels may be packed or unpacked (spaced out to byte or word boundaries), depending on the format or device requirements.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Depending on the color depth, a pixel in the picture will occupy at least *n*/8 bytes, where *n* is the bit depth.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] where width and height are given in pixels.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] In the formula above, header size and color palette size, if any, are not included.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Due to effects of row padding to align each row start to a storage unit boundary, such as a word, additional bytes may be needed.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Microsoft has defined a particular representation of color bitmaps of different color depths, as an aid to exchanging bitmaps between devices and applications with a variety of internal representations.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] They called these device-independent bitmaps "DIBs", and the file format for them is called DIB file format or BMP file format.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Here, "device independent" refers to the format, or storage arrangement, and should not be confused with device-independent color.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] The X Window System uses a similar XBM format for black-and-white images, and XPM (*pixelmap*) for color images.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Numerous other uncompressed bitmap file formats are in use, though most not widely.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] For most purposes, standardized compressed bitmap files such as GIF, PNG, TIFF, and JPEG are used.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Lossless compression in particular provides the same information as a bitmap in a smaller file size.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] TIFF is usually either uncompressed, or lossless Lempel–Ziv–Welch compressed like GIF.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] PNG uses deflate lossless compression, another Lempel-Ziv variant.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] There are also a variety of "raw" image files, which store raw bitmaps with no other information.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/bitmap] Such raw files are just bitmaps in files, often with no header or size information (they are distinct from photographic raw image formats, which store raw unprocessed sensor data in a structured container such as TIFF format along with extensive image metadata).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] In computer science, an **FM-index** is a compressed full-text substring index based on the Burrows–Wheeler transform, with some similarities to the suffix array.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] It was created by Paolo Ferragina and Giovanni Manzini, who describe it as an opportunistic data structure as it allows compression of the input text while still permitting fast substring queries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The name stands for Full-text index in Minute space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] It can be used to efficiently find the number of occurrences of a pattern within the compressed text, as well as locate the position of each occurrence.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The query time, as well as the required storage space, has a sublinear complexity with respect to the size of the input data.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The original authors have devised improvements to their original approach and dubbed it "FM-Index version 2".
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] A further improvement, the alphabet-friendly FM-index, combines the use of compression boosting and wavelet trees to significantly reduce the space usage for large alphabets.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The FM-index has found use in, among other places, bioinformatics.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] Using an index is a common strategy to efficiently search a large body of text.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] When the text is larger than what reasonably fits within a computer's main memory, there is a need to compress not only the text but also the index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] When the FM-index was introduced, there were several suggested solutions that were based on traditional compression methods and tried to solve the compressed matching problem.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] In contrast, the FM-index is a compressed self-index, which means that it compresses the data and indexes it at the same time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] An FM-index is created by first taking the Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT) of the input text.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] For example, the BWT of the string T = "abracadabra$" is "ard$rcaaaabb", and here it is represented by the matrix M where each row is a rotation of the text, and the rows have been sorted lexicographically.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The transform corresponds to the concatenation of the characters from the last column (labeled L).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The BWT in itself allows for some compression with, for instance, move to front and Huffman encoding, but the transform has even more uses.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The rows in the matrix are essentially the sorted suffixes of the text and the first column F of the matrix shares similarities with suffix arrays.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] How the suffix array relates to the BWT lies at the heart of the FM-index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] It is possible to make a last-to-first column mapping LF(i) from an index i to an index j, such that F[j] = L[i], with the help of a table C[c] and a function Occ(c, k).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The last-to-first mapping can now be defined as LF(i) = C[L[i]] + Occ(L[i], i).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] For instance, on row 9, L is a and the same a can be found on row 5 in the first column F, so LF(9) should be 5 and LF(9) = C[a] + Occ(a, 9) = 5.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] For any row i of the matrix, the character in the last column L[i] precedes the character in the first column F[i] also in T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] Finally, if L[i] = T[k], then L[LF(i)] = T[k - 1], and using the equality it is possible to extract a string of T from L.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The FM-index itself is a compression of the string L together with C and Occ in some form, as well as information that maps a selection of indices in L to positions in the original string T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The operation *count* takes a pattern P[1..p] and returns the number of occurrences of that pattern in the original text T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] Since the rows of matrix M are sorted, and it contains every suffix of T, the occurrences of pattern P will be next to each other in a single continuous range.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The operation iterates backwards over the pattern.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] For every character in the pattern, the range that has the character as a suffix is found.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The new range is [C[r] + Occ(r, start-1) + 1 ..
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] 10 + 2] = [11..12], if start is the index of the beginning of the range and end is the end.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] This range over L is all the characters of T that have suffixes beginning with *ra*.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The new range is [C[b] + Occ(b, start-1) + 1 ..
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] This range over L is all the characters that have a suffix that begins with *bra*.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] Now that the whole pattern has been processed, the count is the same as the size of the range: 8 - 7 + 1 = 2.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] If the range becomes empty or the range boundaries cross each other before the whole pattern has been looked up, the pattern does not occur in T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] Because Occ(c, k) can be performed in constant time, count can complete in linear time in the length of the pattern: O(p) time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The operation *locate* takes as input an index of a character in L and returns its position i in T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] To locate every occurrence of a pattern, first the range of character is found whose suffix is the pattern in the same way the *count* operation found the range.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] Then the position of every character in the range can be located.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] To map an index in L to one in T, a subset of the indices in L are associated with a position in T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] If L[j] has a position associated with it, locate(j) is trivial.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] If it's not associated, the string is followed with LF(i) until an associated index is found.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] By associating a suitable number of indices, an upper bound can be found.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] *Locate* can be implemented to find *occ* occurrences of a pattern P[1..*p*] in a text T[1..*u*] in O(*p* + *occ* logε *u*) time with $O\left(H_{k}(T)+{{\log \log u} \over {\log ^{\epsilon }u}}\right)$ bits per input symbol for any *k* ≥ 0.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/fm-index] The FM-Index is available in multiple languages, including C++, Java and Rust.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] In computer science, a **range minimum query** (**RMQ**) solves the problem of finding the minimal value in a sub-array of an array of comparable objects.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Range minimum queries have several use cases in computer science, such as the lowest common ancestor problem and the longest common prefix problem (LCP).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Given an array *A*[1 … *n*] of n objects taken from a totally ordered set, such as integers, the range minimum query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) =arg min *A*[*k*] (with 1 ≤ *l* ≤ *k* ≤ *r* ≤ *n*) returns the position of the minimal element in the specified sub-array *A*[*l* … *r*].
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] In a typical setting, the array A is static, i.e., elements are not inserted or deleted during a series of queries, and the queries to be answered on-line (i.e., the whole set of queries are not known in advance to the algorithm).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] In this case a suitable preprocessing of the array into a data structure ensures faster query answering.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] A naive solution is to precompute all possible queries, i.e. the minimum of all sub-arrays of A, and store these in an array B such that *B*[*i*, *j*] = min(*A*[*i*…*j*]); then a range min query can be solved in constant time by array lookup in B.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] There are Θ(*n*²) possible queries for a length-n array, and the answers to these can be computed in Θ(*n*²) time by dynamic programming.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] As in the solution above, answering queries in constant time will be achieved by pre-computing results.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] However, the array will store pre-computed range minimum queries not for every range [*i*, *j*], but only for ranges whose size is a power of two.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] There are O(log *n*) such queries for each start position i, so the size of the dynamic programming table B is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] After this pre-computing step, a query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) can now be answered in constant time by splitting it into two separate queries: one is the pre-computed query with range from l to the largest memoized value smaller than r.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] The other is the query of an interval of the same length that has r as its right boundary.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] These intervals may overlap, but since we are trying to compute the minimum rather than, for example, the sum of the numbers in the array, this does not matter.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] The overall result can thus be obtained, after the linearithmic time pre-computing, in constant time: the two queries can be answered in constant time and the only thing left to do is to choose the smaller of the two results.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] This solution does pre-computation in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Its data structures use *O*(*n*) space and its data structures can be used to answer queries in logarithmic time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] The array is first conceptually divided into blocks of size *s* = ⁠log *n*/4⁠.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Then the minimum for each block can be computed in *O*(*n*) time overall and the minima are stored in a new array.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] For example, using the array *A* = [0,5,2,5,4,3,1,6,3] and a block size of 3 (for illustrative purposes only) yields the minimum array *A'* = [0,3,1].
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Using the solution above, the sub-queries inside the blocks that are not fully contained in the query still need to be answered in constant time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] There are at most two of those blocks: the block containing l and the block containing r.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Constant time is achieved by storing the Cartesian trees for all the blocks in the array.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] For every such tree, the possible result for all queries need to be stored.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] This comes down to *s*2 or *O*(log2 *n*) entries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] This means the overall size of the table is *O*(*n*).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] To look up results efficiently, the Cartesian tree (row) corresponding to a specific block must be addressable in constant time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] The solution is to store the results for all trees in an array and find a unique projection from binary trees to integers to address the entries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] This can be achieved by doing a breadth-first-search through the tree and adding leaf nodes so that every existing node in the Cartesian tree has exactly two children.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] The integer is then generated by representing every inner node as a 0-bit and every leaf as a 1-bit in a bit-word (by traversing the tree in level-order again).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] This leads to a size of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ for every tree.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] To enable random access in constant time to any tree, the trees not contained in the original array need to be included as well.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] An array with indices of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ bits length has size 2⁠log *n*/4⁠ = *O*(*n*).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] RMQs are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Several applications can be found in Fischer and Heun (2007).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] RMQs can be used to solve the lowest common ancestor problem and are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] The LCA query LCA*S*(*v*, *w*) of a rooted tree *S* = (*V*, *E*) and two nodes *v*, *w* ∈ *V* returns the deepest node u (which may be v or w) on paths from the root to both w and v.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Gabow, Bentley, and Tarjan (1984) showed that the LCA Problem can be reduced in linear time to the RMQ problem.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] It follows that, like the RMQ problem, the LCA problem can be solved in constant time and linear space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] In the context of text indexing, RMQs can be used to find the LCP (longest common prefix), where LCP*T*(*i*, *j*) computes the LCP of the suffixes that start at indexes i and j in T.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] To do this we first compute the suffix array A, and the inverse suffix array *A*−1.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] We then compute the LCP array H giving the LCP of adjacent suffixes in A.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/range-minimum-query] Once these data structures are computed, and RMQ preprocessing is complete, the length of the general LCP can be computed in constant time by the formula: LCP(*i*, *j*) = RMQH(*A*-1[*i*] + 1, *A*-1[*j*]), where we assume for simplicity that *A*-1[*i*] + 1 <= *A*-1[*j*] (otherwise swap).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] In computer science, a **succinct data structure** is a data structure which uses an amount of space that is "close" to the information-theoretic lower bound, but (unlike other compressed representations) still allows for efficient query operations.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The concept was originally introduced by Jacobson to encode bit vectors, (unlabeled) trees, and planar graphs.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Unlike general lossless data compression algorithms, succinct data structures retain the ability to use them in-place, without decompressing them first.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A related notion is that of a compressed data structure, insofar as the size of the stored or encoded data similarly depends upon the specific content of the data itself.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Suppose that Z is the information-theoretical optimal number of bits needed to store some data.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] For example, a data structure that uses $2Z$ bits of storage is compact, $Z+{\sqrt {Z}}$ bits is succinct, $Z+\lg Z$ bits is also succinct, and $Z+3$ bits is implicit.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Implicit structures are thus usually reduced to storing information using some permutation of the input data; the most well-known example of this is the heap.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Succinct indexable dictionaries, also called *rank/select* dictionaries, form the basis of a number of succinct representation techniques, including binary trees, k -ary trees and multisets, as well as suffix trees and arrays.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] In other words, $\mathbf {rank} _{q}(x)$ returns the number of elements equal to q up to position x while $\mathbf {select} _{q}(x)$ returns the position of the x -th occurrence of q .
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] There is a simple representation which uses $n+o(n)$ bits of storage space (the original bit array and an $o(n)$ auxiliary structure) and supports **rank** and **select** in constant time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] It uses an idea similar to that for range-minimum queries; there are a constant number of recursions before stopping at a subproblem of a limited size.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The bit array B is partitioned into *large blocks* of size $l=\lg ^{2}n$ bits and *small blocks* of size $s=\lg n/2$ bits.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] For each large block, the rank of its first bit is stored in a separate table $R_{l}[0\dots n/l)$ ; each such entry takes $\lg n$ bits for a total of $(n/l)\lg n=n/\lg n$ bits of storage.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Within a large block, another directory $R_{s}[0\dots l/s)$ stores the rank of each of the $l/s=2\lg n$ small blocks it contains.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The difference here is that it only needs $\lg l=\lg \lg ^{2}n=2\lg \lg n$ bits for each entry, since only the differences from the rank of the first bit in the containing large block need to be stored.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Thus, this table takes a total of $(n/s)\lg l=4n\lg \lg n/\lg n$ bits.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A lookup table $R_{p}$ can then be used that stores the answer to every possible rank query on a bit string of length s for $i\in [0,s)$ ; this requires $2^{s}s\lg s=O({\sqrt {n}}\lg n\lg \lg n)$ bits of storage space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Thus, since each of these auxiliary tables take $o(n)$ space, this data structure supports rank queries in $O(1)$ time and $n+o(n)$ bits of space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] In practice, the lookup table $R_{p}$ can be replaced by bitwise operations and smaller tables that can be used to find the number of bits set in the small blocks.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This is often beneficial, since succinct data structures find their uses in large data sets, in which case cache misses become much more frequent and the chances of the lookup table being evicted from closer CPU caches becomes higher.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Select queries can be easily supported by doing a binary search on the same auxiliary structure used for **rank**; however, this takes $O(\lg n)$ time in the worst case.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A more complicated structure using $3n/\lg \lg n+O({\sqrt {n}}\lg n\lg \lg n)=o(n)$ bits of additional storage can be used to support **select** in constant time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] In practice, many of these solutions have hidden constants in the $O(\cdot )$ notation which dominate before any asymptotic advantage becomes apparent; implementations using broadword operations and word-aligned blocks often perform better in practice.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] There is a succinct (static) dictionary which attains this bound, namely using ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+o({\mathcal {B}}(m,n))$ space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This structure can be extended to support **rank** and **select** queries and takes ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m+n\lg \lg n/\lg n)$ space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Correct **rank** queries in this structure are however limited to elements contained in the set, analogous to how minimal perfect hashing functions work.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This bound can be reduced to a space/time tradeoff by reducing the storage space of the dictionary to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(nt^{t}/\lg ^{t}n+n^{3/4})$ with queries taking $O(t)$ time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] If one wishes to support insertions and deletions, it is possible to achieve a space bound of ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(n/2^{(\log n)^{\Omega (1)}})$ while supporting each operation (insertion, deletion, rank, or select) in expected time $O(1+\log n/\log \log m)$ .
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] It is also possible to construct a indexible dictionary supporting rank (but not select) that uses fewer than $\textstyle {\mathcal {B}}(m,n)$ bits, so long as rank queries are limited to elements contained in the set.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Such a dictionary is called a *monotone minimal perfect hash function*, and can be implemented using as few as $O(m\log \log \log n)$ bits.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A succinct hash table, also known as a *succinct unordered dictionary,* is a data structure that stores m keys from a universe $\{0,1,\dots ,n-1\}$ using space $(1+o(1)){\mathcal {B}}(m,n)$ bits, and while supporting membership queries in constant expected time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The first dynamic succinct hash table was due to Raman and Rao in 2003.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] In the case where $n={\text{poly}}(m)$ , their solution uses space ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m\log \log m)$ bits.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Subsequently, it was shown that this space bound could be improved to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m\log \log \log \cdots \log m)$ bits for any constant number of logarithms and a little after that this bound was also optimal.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The latter solution supports all operations in worst-case constant time with high probability.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The first static succinct hash table was due to Pagh in 1999.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] In the case where $n={\text{poly}}(m)$ , their solution uses space ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m(\log \log m)^{2}/\log m)$ bits, and supports *worst-case* constant-time queries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This bound was subsequently improved to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+m/{\text{poly}}\log m$ bits, and then to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+{\text{poly}}\log m$ bits.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Whereas the first two solutions support worst-case constant-time queries, the final one supports constant expected-time queries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The final solution also requires access to a lookup table of size $n^{\epsilon }$ , but this lookup table is independent of the set of elements being stored.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] More recently, Hu et al. devised a solution that uses space ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+n^{\epsilon }$ while supporting worst-case constant-time queries.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A string with an arbitrary length (Pascal string) takes *Z* + log(*Z*) space, and is thus succinct.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] When a sequence of variable-length items (such as strings) needs to be encoded, there are various possibilities.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A direct approach is to store a length and an item in each record – these can then be placed one after another.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This allows efficient next, but not finding the *k*th item.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] An alternative is to place the items in order with a delimiter (e.g., null-terminated string).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This uses a delimiter instead of a length, and is substantially slower, since the entire sequence must be scanned for delimiters.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] An alternative approach is out-of-band separation: the items can simply be placed one after another, with no delimiters.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Item bounds can then be stored as a sequence of length, or better, offsets into this sequence.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Alternatively, a separate binary string consisting of 1s in the positions where an item begins, and 0s everywhere else is encoded along with it.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] Given this string, the $select$ function can quickly determine where each item begins, given its index.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] This is *compact* but not *succinct,* as it takes 2*Z* space, which is O(*Z*).
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] The number of different binary trees on n nodes is ${\tbinom {2n}{n}}$ $/(n+1)$ .
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] For large n , this is about $4^{n}$ ; thus we need at least about $\log _{2}(4^{n})=2n$ bits to encode it.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/succinct-data-structure] A succinct binary tree therefore would occupy only 2 bits per node.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] The **wavelet tree** is a succinct data structure to store strings in compressed space.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] It generalizes the $\mathbf {rank} _{q}$ and $\mathbf {select} _{q}$ operations defined on bitvectors to arbitrary alphabets.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] Originally introduced to represent compressed suffix arrays, it has found application in several contexts.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] The tree is defined by recursively partitioning the alphabet into pairs of subsets; the leaves correspond to individual symbols of the alphabet, and at each node a bitvector stores whether a symbol of the string belongs to one subset or the other.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] The name derives from an analogy with the wavelet transform for signals, which recursively decomposes a signal into low-frequency and high-frequency components.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] Let $\Sigma$ be a finite alphabet with $\sigma ={|\Sigma |}$ .
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] By using succinct dictionaries in the nodes, a string $s\in \Sigma ^{*}$ can be stored in ${|s|}H_{0}(s)+o({|s|}\log \sigma )$ , where $H_{0}(s)$ is the order-0 empirical entropy of s .
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] If the tree is balanced, the operations $\mathbf {access}$ , $\mathbf {rank} _{q}$ , and $\mathbf {select} _{q}$ can be supported in $O(\log \sigma )$ time.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] A wavelet tree contains a bitmap representation of a string.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] If we know the alphabet set, then the exact string can be inferred by tracking bits down the tree.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] In this context, the rank of a position i in a bitvector b is the number of ones that appear in the first i positions of b .
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] Because the rank can be calculated in O(1) by using succinct dictionaries, any S[i] in string S can be accessed in $O(\log \sigma )$ time, as long as the tree is balanced.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] Several extensions to the basic structure have been presented in the literature.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] To reduce the height of the tree, multiary nodes can be used instead of binary.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] The data structure can be made dynamic, supporting insertions and deletions at arbitrary points of the string; this feature enables the implementation of dynamic FM-indexes.
[src:wavelet-tree-succinct/wavelet-tree] This can be further generalized, allowing the update operations to change the underlying alphabet: the Wavelet Trie exploits the trie structure on an alphabet of strings to enable dynamic tree modifications.
